main event: On June 8, 1959, a witness in Washington, D.C. observed a bright, high-speed, silvery, circular to saucer-shaped object traveling from southeast to northwest at an estimated speed of over 1,000 mph.
interesting points: The object was about 20-30 feet in diameter and appeared bright and metallic.
The object was visible for 15-20 minutes and appeared to accelerate and climb out of sight.
The object was detected by Coast Guard radar at an altitude of 11,500 feet and a velocity of 1,575 mph.
The object was also observed by a Traffic Control Center, which reported an object identical to the one detected by the Coast Guard radar.
After analysis, it was concluded that the object was probably a meteor or natural re-entry phenomenon.
sighted object: a bright, high-speed, silvery, circular to saucer-shaped object
witnesses: multiple, including a witness and radar observations
